Join me today as I fly the 747-400. Not only that, but this is the last one flying in Asiana‚Äôs fleet. I don‚Äôt know why they‚Äôve kept just one, and I don‚Äôt know why they only fly it between Osaka and Seoul these days, but I‚Äôm not asking too many questions because it means I get to fly it! I figured out a nice way to get home from Osaka: Seoul is a good place to book cheap business class tickets from, and I found a $1600 Emirates ticket all the way back to Stockholm from there. So tacking on this 747 to the itinerary was a no-brainer, even though this made my trip stretch to 32 hours in total. The things we do to fly special planes eh? Kansai International Airport is built on a massive man-made island out in Osaka Bay, and you have to cross a long bridge to get to it. The airport is in need of a refresh ‚Äì it looks and feels old and a little neglected. I‚Äôm in seat 3A in the nose of theis 747, what used to be Asiana‚Äôs international First Class, but is now sold as business class. Bit of a waste to have all this space on a flight that‚Äôs barely over an hour, but I‚Äôm going to make the most of it. We get just enough post-sunset light still in the sky for some nice views after takeoff. And they serve a full meal which is quite good. Especially because it comes with gochujang sauce. I also manage three gin & tonics on this flight. That takes some dedication guys. Check out the old-school metallic sink lavs too. Kind of classic and cool! It was a lovely, if too short, flight on the 747. Let me know what you think! And thanks for coming along!
